A virtual environment is like a separate Python workspace for one project.
Without virtual environments:

Project A uses pandas 1.x
Project B uses pandas 2.x

Both packages may conflict if installed globally.

With virtual environment:
project_a/.venv  -> its own packages
project_b/.venv  -> its own packages


create virtual environment:
- inside my project folder: python -m venv .venv
- creates a folder: .venv/
It contains a separate Python + installed packages for this project.

activate virtual environment:
bash: source .venv/bin/activate

